SIMPLE: overset
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overset
<hw>O`ver*set"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Overset</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Oversetting</conjf>. ]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn or tip
(anything) over from an upright, or a proper, position so that it lies
upon its side or bottom upwards; to upset; <as>as, to <ex>overset</ex> a
chair, a coach, a ship, or a building</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to fall, or to fail; to subvert; to
overthrow; <as>as, to <ex>overset</ex> a government or a
plot</as>.</def> <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fill too full.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Howell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overset
<hw>O`ver*set"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To turn, or to be turned,
over; to be upset.</def> <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overset</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Overset
<hw>O"ver*set`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
upsetting; overturn; overthrow; <as>as, the <ex>overset</ex> of a
carriage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An excess; superfluity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧This <xex>overset</xex> of wealth and pomp. ⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp.
Burnel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>oversewn</ent>⟦br⟧
